spans.text: of chains , Where life is death
the dread sound of groans and clank of chains , Where life is death , and day perpetual night ,
life , yet not allowed to die

Who dart with more than tygers' savage rage On pining sickness , or decrepid age : Can such a wretch with trembling hand assay His mansion and companions to portray , And griefs proclaim which never have met the day
such a wretch with trembling hand
which never have met the day
which no tongue can speak , or pencil paint
which no tongue can speak , or pencil paint
Where murderers dire lie shackled to the ground , And innocence and guilt alike
I to my sad companions gain One ray of hope
lines in Heaven's own language dressed
want in silent anguish dwells , There
the slaves of pomp and grandeur
What streams of comfort from their wealth might flow
an offering pure and neat , A blessed memorial and an odour sweet
the orphan's tear To Heaven ascend , an offering pure and neat , A blessed memorial and an odour sweet , Recorded
this dread abode Do you never think of an offended God
that pardon , which the world denies

by her distaff earn that homely bread , By which our helpless children long were fed : She bade me hope by industry set free , No gripping landlord need we dread to see , She taught me to suppress the rising sigh , And checked the tear when starting from mine eye ; She over my limbs her thread-worn garment spread , And with her infants clothes sustained my head , While at my feet those infants playful smiled , And by their prattle oft my pains beguiled ! — Ah ! helpless babes , ah ! wretched , dearest wife
that no danger's near , No more my playful infants cheer my sight , Here all is horror and perpetual night
feel them cling around my trembling knees , While on their helpless parent bailiffs seize , Still , still I hear my wife
some mercy ere it be too late
earning food to save each infant's life
those infants of a mother's care
her vent her agony of soul

these distract my brain , Thoughts , which heap woe on woe , and pain on pain ; No ! rather let me , with imploring eye , Look up to Him , who hears the pris'ner's sigh ; To Him , who calls the weary and oppressed , To come to Him for succour and for rest
one pitying friend or comfort nigh
